Yet Pythagoras did not conceive friendship as a simple individual affection, but as an universal benevolence which should be extended to all men in general, and to all good people.‘ At that time he gave to this virtue the name of philanthropy. It is the virtue which, under the name of charity, serves as foundation for the Christian religion. Jesus offers it to his disciples immediately after divine love, and as equal to piety.‘¹ Zoroaster places it after sincer- ity⁶; he wished that man might be pure in thought, speech, and acti0n; that he might speak the truth, and that he might do good to all men.
